"{\n  \"missions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"3\",\n      \"title\": \"Rung Debts\",\n      \"quest_giver\": {\"name\": \"Keth of the Nets\", \"affiliation\": \"Black Net Syndicate\"},\n      \"description\": \"Moonless nights turn the Ribsward Bazaar into a skyscape of bottled constellations, each eel-jar a trembling star hung from bone-ladders and awnings remembered from storms gone by. Between the stalls where resin smokes and amberglass glows, coded melodies drift like nets cast across conversation, tugging the wary toward safe lanes and warning those who have too much to hide. Sere Kallin moves with the old Warden cadence and the newer, quieter footfall of someone who has learned the price of being seen; her buckler catches shards of green light, and her stormglass whistle hums once as if to acknowledge the city’s held breath. Keth of the Nets waits at the lip of a cracked rib, smiling in that cut-thin way that suggests mercy and debt are merely different weaves in the same rope, and he speaks of a small errand dressed in reverence: a prayer-packet sealed in wax, to be slipped through a maintenance rung and tucked into a cracked conduit close enough to the Heartward Engine to feel its measured pulse. He calls it a whisper, but Sere remembers the red tide and the way the Engine sang the city into panic, and she knows some whispers are shaped like keys; this one is a pulse pattern etched into saint-glass, a rhythm designed to coax open a drowned water gate that the Tidemothers insist must remain sleeping. The rung-path he offers is old and secret, a tunnel sealed with wax that bends away from watchlamps, its floor polished by contraband feet and its ceiling close enough to kiss; it leads through the city’s marrow where bone pistons boom like distant thunder and every breath fogs into prayer. Wardens prowl the edges of this territory, not fully welcome and never fully absent, and rumor says the Crown Gate jaw can grind shut on a traitor’s ankle faster than any man can shout for mercy. What Keth truly offers, under the polite veil of trade, is a loosening of the knots that bind Sere’s name to ledgers and a chance to pull one thread free before the whole net tightens, but every gift tied to the Engine drips with consequence. She must choose in the dim thrum of the city’s heart: deliver the whisper and earn clean ledgers, break the glass and draw ire enough to salt her sleep, or carve a new rhythm with stormglass and pilot lore, risking a lesser opening that answers to her call once. And if anyone watches from the shadows—some Black Net lookout eager to shine in Keth’s ledger—she must leave behind only the hush of water and a trail scoured so clean that even old friends in Warden gray could not swear she ever walked that rung at all.\",\n      \"objectives\": [\n        \"Meet Keth of the Nets at the Ribsward Bazaar and receive the sealed prayer-packet.\",\n        \"Trace the wax-sealed rib tunnel toward the Heartward Engine without attracting the Wardens.\",\n        \"Decide whether to plant the packet in the cracked conduit, destroy it, or alter the pattern with your stormglass shard.\",\n        \"Confront a Black Net lookout if discovered and leave no trail that leads back to your old Warden patrol.\"\n      ],\n      \"dialogue\": [\n        {\"speaker\": \"Keth of the Nets\", \"lines\": \"Weigh your choices like salt, Sere, grain by grain, because too much at once blinds the tongue and ruins the stew. What I am asking is smaller than fear and larger than pride, a hush wrapped in wax that only needs your steady hands and your old knack for walking where hooks don’t catch. You do not need to know its hymn, and in truth, knowing would only paint targets on both our backs and invite questions that end in rooms with no windows. Debts climb bone ladders faster than feet, and you have a few rungs left before the drop; I offer you a rope, and I won’t even ask you to count the knots aloud. Walk the maintenance rung, tuck the whisper into the crack that thirsts for it, and I will loosen the ledger that whistles your name like a curse each time a collector turns a page. Think of your mother’s brace when the rain comes in off the Nine Mouths, and imagine that ache softened by kindness that doesn’t ask to be named in public, only remembered in the right tavern when a favor tries to grow teeth again.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Sere Kallin\", \"lines\": \"I’ve carried better for worse men and worse for better women, and I’ve learned that mercy often comes wrapped in the same cloth as bait. Do not gild this as charity, Keth, because the city’s heart hears lies as clearly as bells and returns them with interest. I have stood on the Skyhook when the chain sang out of season and felt my bones answer, and I have heard the Engine’s breath stutter like a sick drummer until the Tidemothers soothed it with songs that tasted of salt and thunder. If I take your packet, it is not because I trust your intentions, but because I trust the rung I can see more than the knife I cannot; at least if I carry it, I have a say in how close it gets to the red pulse. And if you had gone to another courier, one hungrier or one who thinks the ribs are only stairs and not a promise, the city would have woken with a new scar and I with a heavier one, so here we are, trading whispers for weather.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Isera Bent-Pike\", \"lines\": \"If I catch you near the Heartward Engine on a night without a writ, I will hold you by the jawbone and ask questions with the patience of a tide carving stone. I taught you the first rule of ribs: do not make them sing unless the city asks, and the city speaks in orders and oaths, not in eel-light bargains. Whatever debts lean on your name, bring them to me like you would a fracture, in daytime and with the truth, and I will set them as clean as I can so the ache dulls when it rains. I did not raise you to trade your oath for a purse’s wink or to be dragged like contraband through tunnels your boots once mapped for patrol. Turn back while the only thing I have to write in my ledger beside your name is worry, and not a report that tastes of betrayal.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Rhy Tidesong\", \"lines\": \"The city’s heart beats because we ask it to in the right way, at the right hour, and with water that knows our names, and anything else is vanity with teeth. Do not be fooled by any who call a pulse a prayer when it is a pry-bar, for gates open to many songs and most of them lead to rooms where drowning wears a crown. If you must walk where the Engine hums its oldest hymns, carry your breath like a promise and keep iron thoughts far from your tongue, for even unspoken words can weigh water toward wrath. There are gates within gates, child of the Nine Mouths, and some were sealed by grief that still stains stone; you cannot know which grief you’ll free until it stands beside you asking what debt you meant to pay. Should your hand tremble when it comes to the glass, sing first, and remember that the deep forgives, but it never forgets a name.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Lur Oghrim\", \"lines\": \"I smell river-reeded caution on you, and I see Warden polish clinging to your stance like barnacles that forgot their ship sank, so do not pretend you’re just another night-seller with a pouch of resin. Keth pays me to count shadows and salt footprints, and he says the one I seek tonight will not flinch when the bones groan, which makes me think you will do. I have eyes in the eel-glow and ears in the bazaar songs, and the tunes tell me a packet is walking that should be carried by hands less scrupulous or more afraid. You could tell me to step aside, and I might, but only if you give me something heavier than fear to weigh against my place in the ledgers and my seat at the nets. Speak now with a truth that tastes of tide, or I will start singing for the Wardens in a key that brings pikes to bear and shuts every rung that doesn’t throw us